Introduction

Modern plant and animal breeding is rapidly shifting toward approaches that leverage genome-wide marker data to predict the genetic merit of individuals. Along this course, this idea began to emerge when we discussed the idea behind interval composite mapping (CIM), where a subset of SNPs was included as cofactors in the model to control background noise. Later, in the GWAS classes, even though each marker was tested individually as a fixed effect in the Q+K model, we introduced the idea of including all markers indirectly by calculating a genomic relationship matrix (GRM)âa way of modeling relatedness based on genome-wide information. Finally, we briefly discussed about more recent GWAS implementations that iteratively selected markers to be included in the model.

Genomic selection (GS) formalizes this concept by assuming that all markers, regardless of their individual effect sizes, contribute to the phenotype and should be used collectively to predict genetic performance. But, there are two important points when considering the implementation on GS models:

  • Differences between inference and prediction;
  • Statistical challenges.

Inference vs.Â prediction: two contrasting approaches in statistics

Here, we touch on another important and sometimes sensitive topic in statistics: the distinction between inference and prediction. In many classical genetic studiesâsuch as QTL mapping or GWASâthe primary goal is inference, meaning we are interested in understanding the underlying biology by identifying specific markers or genomic regions that are statistically associated with a trait. In this context, the aim is to estimate the effect of individual markers, test their significance, and draw conclusions about causality or biological relevance.

In contrast, genomic selection (GS) shifts the focus from inference to prediction. The goal in GS is not necessarily to know which markers are responsible for a trait, but rather to build a model that can accurately predict the phenotypic performance of individuals whose phenotypes have not yet been observed. In this predictive framework, we are less concerned with the statistical significance or interpretability of individual marker effects. Instead, we focus on the overall accuracy of the model and its ability to generalize to new data.

This distinction is crucial when choosing statistical methods. Inference-oriented models prioritize transparency, interpretability, and hypothesis testing, while prediction-oriented models emphasize robustness, regularization, and generalization. Genomic selection belongs to the latter categoryâits success is measured not by p-values, but by how well it predicts real-world outcomes like yield, quality, or disease resistance in new genotypes.

Curse of dimensionality

Along this classes, we will discuss the fact that GS presents unique statistical challenges. In typical genomic datasets, the number of markers (p) far exceeds the number of observations (n)âa situation known as p >> n. This leads to a lack of degrees of freedom, making classical approaches like ordinary least squares (OLS) inapplicable. Additionally, high collinearity among markers complicates parameter estimation, as the model cannot separate the effects of correlated SNPs cleanly.

To address these challenges, Bayesian methods are commonly used in genomic prediction. Unlike frequentist approaches, Bayesian statistics naturally incorporate prior information into the model. This provides a built-in mechanism for regularization, shrinking marker effect estimates toward zero based on prior distributions. In practice, this means we can still make reliable predictions even in high-dimensional settings, where traditional methods would fail.

Overall, genomic selection represents a paradigm shift: rather than identifying a few âimportantâ genes, we embrace the whole genome as a predictorâan approach made possible by high-throughput genotyping and advances in statistical modeling.

Linear Regression

The simplest regression models is linear with a single predictor:

\[y=\beta_0+\beta_1x+e\]

  • The terms \(\beta_0\) and \(\beta_1\), are the intercept and slope of the model, respectively.

  • Intercept is the point at which the line crosses the y axis at x = 0. It is also the mean, specifically the conditional mean, of y for individuals with values of 0 on x.

  • The slope expresses the relationship between y and x. Positive slope values indicate that larger values of x are associated with correspondingly larger values of y, while negative slopes mean that larger x values are associated with smaller y values. Holding everything else constant, larger values of slope (positive or negative) indicate a stronger linear relationship between y and x.

  • Error represents the random error inherent in any statistical model, including regression. It expresses the fact that for any individual, the model will not generally provide a perfect predicted value of y.

This same model can be written using different notations. For example:

  • Matrix notation: \(y=X\beta+e\), where \(X_{N\times K}\) is matrix of predictors with dimension N (sample size) by K (number os predictiors).

  • Probabilistically: \(y_i \sim N(\beta_0 + \beta_1x_i, \sigma^2)\), where the The parameter \(\sigma^2\) represents the variability with which the outcomes deviate from their predictions based on the model. This nomenclature is more common in Bayesian description.

Regression Models in a Frequentist Framework

In all real-world contexts, the population is unavailable to the researcher. Therefore, \(\beta_0\) and \(\beta_1\) must be estimated using sample data taken from the population. The statistical literature describes several methods for obtaining estimated values of the regression model parameters given a set of x and y.

Ordinary Least Squares (OLS)

  • By far, OLS is the most popular and widely used approach for inference.
  • The goal of OLS is to minimize the sum of the squared differences (RSS) between the observed values of y and the model predicted values of y across the sample.

\[\hat{\beta} = (X'X)^{-1} X'y\]

Maximum Likelihood

  • If the errors from the linear model are independent and normally distributed, then the OLS is also the maximum likelihood estimate. Technically, maximizing the likelihood requires minimizing the sum of squared residuals.
  • The likelihood function in a regression model is defined as the probability density of the data given the parameters and predictors.

\[p(y|\beta_0,\beta_1,\sigma^2,x) = \prod^n_{i=1} N(y_i|\beta_0+\beta_1x_i,\sigma^2)\]

Regression in a Bayesian Context

Motivation

  • Incorporating prior information
  • Bayesian inference expresses uncertainty using probability
  • OLS tends to overfit when p is large, Bayesâ use of prior tends to make it more conservative.

Mathematically

\[p(\beta_0, \beta_1, \sigma^2 \mid y) = \dfrac{p(y \mid \beta_0,\beta_1, \sigma^2) \times p(\beta_0,\beta_1,\sigma^2)}{p(y)}\]

  • \(p(\beta_0, \beta_1\sigma^2 \mid y)\) : posterior distribution

  • \(p(y \mid \beta_0,\beta_1, \sigma^2)\): likelihood

  • \(p(\beta_0,\beta_1,\sigma^2)\): prior for the parameters

  • \(p(y)\): evidence

Graphical Representation

From the diagram, it is easy to see that the response is modeled as a normal distribution with mean (\(\mu_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1X_i\)) and standard deviation \(\sigma^2\). To make Bayesian estimation possible, we need to assign prior distributions to all model parameters, thus making our assumptions about the parameters explicit. We need to specify an appropriate likelihood, which is the normal likelihood function. The likelihood component is the part that incorporates the data. Bayesâ rule can be applied in order to update the priors to the posterior distributions, which reï¬ect the distribution of credible parameter values taken into account the data.

Probabilistic formulation of the simple linear regression model. Same example presented by Kruschke (2014), where the parameters in the model are presented in the hierarchial form to represent distributions and probabilities associated to the Bayesian framework. From this example, it is easy to see how a linear regression model coulb be expressed in terms of prior information T0, T1 and G.

Why we need to use MCMC for Simple Regression

To answers this question, letâs look first to a normal probability density function.

\[p(y\mid\mu,\sigma) = \dfrac{1}{\sigma\sqrt{2\pi}} e^{-\frac{(x-\mu)^2}{2\sigma^2} }\]

To get an intuition for the normal distribution as a likelihood function, we will consider the same example presented by Kruschke (2014), where three data values y1 = 85, y2 = 100, and y3 = 115 were considered. The Figure shows \(p(D\mid \mu, \sigma )\) for different values of \(\mu\) and \(\sigma\) . As you can see, there are values of that make the data most probable, but others no. The question is, given the data, how should we allocate credibility to combinations of \(\mu\) and \(\sigma\)?

Probabilistic formulation of the simple linear regression model

The answer this question we need to use the Bayesâ rule and solve the follow equation:

\[p(\mu,\sigma \mid D) = \dfrac{p(D\mid\mu,\sigma) \ p(\mu,\sigma)}{\iint d\mu\ d\sigma\ p(D\mid\mu,\sigma)\ p(\mu,\sigma)}\]

The reason for this analytic intractability stems essentially from difficulty in computing the denominator of the Bayesâ rule application. In the case of the posterior distribution expressed by the equation, the denominator requires that we integrate the numerator over the bivariate prior distribution for \(\mu\) and \(\sigma\) which is to say, we have to compute this two-dimensional integral. In the case of simple regression this is a three-dimensional integral that involves \(\beta_0\), \(\beta_1\) and \(\sigma^2\). Now, image in case of multiple regressions?

Some solutions for that:

  • Conjugate prior distributions. Be prepared for mathematics. Gelman et al., (2013) and Hoff (2009) are both good books with intuitive examples
  • Program your own MCMC. Be prepared\(^2\) !!
  • Probabilistic programming language that is a system that automatically builds MCMC samples for complex models. Best suited for users who do not want to delve into mathematical details. Below, some examples of programming languages:
    • BUGS
    • JAGS
    • INLA
    • Stan

Hands-on

We will not use any software at this point. The idea is just to show how we can navigate over different estimation methods in the regression framework and get the same results.

Parameter Estimation

Frequentist Approach

We will assume a basic linear regression:

\[y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x + \varepsilon,\quad \varepsilon \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \sigma^2)\] Ordinary Least Squares (OLS)

\[\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}} = (\mathbf{X}^\top \mathbf{X})^{-1} \mathbf{X}^\top \mathbf{y}\] Maximum Likelihood (MLE)

Assuming normal errors:

\[\mathcal{L}(\beta_0, \beta_1, \sigma^2) = \prod_{i=1}^n \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma^2}} \exp\left( -\frac{(y_i - \beta_0 - \beta_1 x_i)^2}{2\sigma^2} \right)\]

\[\log \mathcal{L} = -\frac{n}{2} \log(2\pi) - \frac{n}{2} \log(\sigma^2) - \frac{1}{2\sigma^2} \sum_{i=1}^n (y_i - \beta_0 - \beta_1 x_i)^2\]

For the MLE, we will use the optim() function in R. This function has a general-purpose optimization tool used to maximize or minimize functions. In the case of MLE, assuming that the error is normally distributed, we will maximize the function to find the best values for the mean (\(\beta\)) and the variance for the simulated data set.

R codes

# --- Simulate data---
set.seed(123)
n <- 100
x <- rnorm(n, mean = 5, sd = 2)
y <- 3 + 1.5 * x + rnorm(n, sd = 1)
X <- cbind(1, x)

# -- OLS ---
# OLS via matrix algebra
beta_hat <- solve(t(X) %*% X) %*% t(X) %*% y
beta_hat
##       [,1]
##   3.028376
## x 1.473764
# Using a function for OLS
ols_model <- lm(y ~ x)
coef(ols_model)
## (Intercept)           x 
##    3.028376    1.473764
# -- OLS ---
neg_log_lik <- function(par, x, y) {
  beta0 <- par[1]
  beta1 <- par[2]
  sigma <- abs(par[3])  # sigma must be positive
  
  y_hat <- beta0 + beta1 * x
  -sum(dnorm(y, mean = y_hat, sd = sigma, log = TRUE))
}

# Initial values: beta0, beta1, sigma
init_par <- c(0, 0, 1)
mle_result <- optim(init_par, neg_log_lik, x = x, y = y)

# MLE estimates
mle_estimates <- mle_result$par
names(mle_estimates) <- c("beta0", "beta1", "sigma")
mle_estimates
##     beta0     beta1     sigma 
## 3.0302401 1.4733250 0.9613375

Bayesian Approach

Important

  • OLS estimates (\(\beta_0\)) and (\(\beta_1\)) by minimizing the sum of squared errors.
  • MLE estimates the same parameters by maximizing the likelihood of the observed data.
  • Bayesian methods estimate a posterior distribution of parameters using:

Elements from the Bayesian extimation

  • Posteriori: \(p(\beta_0, \beta_1, \sigma^2 \mid y, x) \propto p(y \mid \beta_0, \beta_1, \sigma^2) \cdot p(\beta_0) \cdot p(\beta_1) \cdot p(\sigma^2)\)

  • Likelihoods: \(p(y \mid \beta_0, \beta_1, \sigma^2) = \prod_{i=1}^n \mathcal{N}(y_i \mid \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_i, \sigma^2)\)

  • Priors:

    • \(\beta_0 \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 100^2)\) (non-informative, large variance)
    • \(\beta_1 \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 100^2)\) (non-informative, large variance)
    • \(\sigma^2 \sim \text{Inverse-Gamma}(a, b)\) (cannot have negative values)

We can write it in a close for given that both prior and likelihood are Gaussian, thus the posterior is also Gaussian. In a matrix notation, the results are:

\[p(\boldsymbol{\beta} \mid \mathbf{y}, \mathbf{X}, \sigma^2) \propto p(\mathbf{y} \mid \mathbf{X}, \boldsymbol{\beta}, \sigma^2) \cdot p(\boldsymbol{\beta})\]

\[\boldsymbol{\beta} \mid \mathbf{y}, \mathbf{X}, \sigma^2 \sim \mathcal{N}(\boldsymbol{\mu}_n, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_n)\]

\[\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_n = \left( \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_0^{-1} + \frac{1}{\sigma^2} \mathbf{X}^\top \mathbf{X} \right)^{-1}\]

\[\boldsymbol{\mu}_n = \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_n \left( \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_0^{-1} \boldsymbol{\mu}_0 + \frac{1}{\sigma^2} \mathbf{X}^\top \mathbf{y} \right)\] R codes

# NON-INFORMATIVE PRIOR
set.seed(123)
# Bayesian linear regression with weak prior
library(MASS)

# Prior
mu0 <- c(0, 0)
Sigma0 <- diag(1e6, 2)

# Estimate sigma^2 from OLS
residuals <- y - X %*% beta_hat
sigma2_hat <- sum(residuals^2) / (n - 2)

# Posterior
Sigma0_inv <- solve(Sigma0)
XtX <- t(X) %*% X
XtY <- t(X) %*% y

Sigma_n <- solve(Sigma0_inv + XtX / sigma2_hat)
mu_n <- Sigma_n %*% (Sigma0_inv %*% mu0 + XtY / sigma2_hat)

# Sample from posterior
samples <- mvrnorm(5000, mu = mu_n, Sigma = Sigma_n)

# Posterior means
colMeans(samples)
##                 x 
## 3.028555 1.473807
# INCLUDING SOME INFORMATIVE PRIOR
mu0_strong <- c(0, 0)
Sigma0_strong <- diag(c(1, 0.1^2))

Sigma0_inv <- solve(Sigma0_strong)
Sigma_n_strong <- solve(Sigma0_inv + XtX / sigma2_hat)
mu_n_strong <- Sigma_n_strong %*% (Sigma0_inv %*% mu0_strong + XtY / sigma2_hat)

samples_strong <- mvrnorm(5000, mu = mu_n_strong, Sigma = Sigma_n_strong)
colMeans(samples_strong)
##                 x 
## 4.417328 1.198039

Postulate a Bayesian Regression

\[y_i = \beta_0 + X_i\beta + e_i\]

  • We can use the coefficients from a fitted regression model to help study to what degree changes in one variable are associated with changes in another.

  • Important: Simple Regression model serves as a didactic example that is sufficient to demonstrate simple regression, but it performs a statistical error by ignoring the within-genotype dependency in this example.

\[firmness_i \sim N(\beta_0+\beta_1\ size_i, \ \sigma^2)\]

Fit the Model

  • Stan is available through a variety of interfaces including rstan in R and PyStan in Python.
  • R package rstanarm.
  • Reference for the R package.

Step 1. Specify the model

  • stan_glm function

  • Specifies the outcome and predictors in the familiar lm formula syntax

  • An intercept is included by default.

  • Assumes that the likelihood is normal (Gaussian) with an identity link function

  • All parameters in a Bayesian modelneed prior distributions

    • Uninformative priors place equal or nearly equal prior weight on all possible values of a parameter.
    • Weakly informative priors provide some information on the relative a priori plausibility of the possible parameter values (help stabilize computations) default of the package
    • Informative prior, when we have a lot of prior knowledge to bring to a problem.

Step 2. Estimate the model parameters

  • Estimate the model parameters.
  • By default, rstanarm uses 4 Markov chains (chains) with 2000 iterations (iter) each, half of which are discarded as âwarm-upâ.
  • For situations in which the estimation algorithm does not converge due to an insufficient number of samples, it may be necessary to draw more samples by increasing the iter argument.

Step 3. Explore the posterior

  • Assess the fit of the model to the data, we can compare the observed data to datasets simulated according to our assumed data generating process and the posterior draws of the model parameters.
  • pp_check function.
  • bayesplot R package is an extensive library of plotting functions for use after fitting Bayesian models

Weakly informative priors

library("rstanarm")
library("ggplot2")
library("broom")
library("bayesplot")


# Run model 1 with stan_glm
SingleLevelModel <- stan_glm(firmness ~ size,  # Similar notation to lm()
                             chains = 4,       # Number of MCMC chains
                             iter = 2000,      # Number of MCMC steps
                             data = dat)

# View summary of priors used
prior_summary(SingleLevelModel)

# Summary of the data
summary(SingleLevelModel)

# Plot the posterior
# posterior <- as.array(SingleLevelModel)
# mcmc_areas(
#   posterior,
#   pars = c("sigma", "size"),
#   prob = 0.8, # 80% intervals
#   prob_outer = 0.99, # 99%
#   point_est = "mean"
# )
# mcmc_hist(posterior, pars = c("sigma", "size", "(Intercept)"))
library(gridExtra)
# Explore the posterior
plot1 = pp_check(SingleLevelModel, nreps = 100) + xlab("firmness")

# modelâs prediction
posterior1 <- as.matrix(SingleLevelModel)
means1 <- colMeans(posterior1)
betas <- posterior1[sample(nrow(posterior1), 100), 1:2]
blues <- color_scheme_get("brightblue")
mod1p1 <- ggplot(dat, aes(x = size, y = firmness)) +
  geom_point(color = "gray30") +
  geom_abline(intercept = betas[, 1], slope = betas[, 2], 
              color = blues[[2]], size = 0.15,  alpha = 0.5
  ) +
  geom_abline(intercept = means1[1], 
              slope = means1[2],size = 1.25,  color = blues[[6]]
) 

# Ploting
grid.arrange(plot1,mod1p1,ncol=2)

Informative priors

library("rstanarm")
library("ggplot2")
library("broom")
library("bayesplot")

# Run model 1 with stan_glm
SingleLevelModelMod <-  stan_glm(
  firmness ~ size,
  data = dat,
  prior = normal(20, 1, autoscale = FALSE),
  prior_intercept = normal(50, 100, autoscale = FALSE),
  iter = 4000,
  adapt_delta = 0.99
)

# View summary of priors used
prior_summary(SingleLevelModelMod)
# Summary of the data
summary(SingleLevelModelMod)
library(gridExtra)
# Explore the posterior
plot1 = pp_check(SingleLevelModelMod, nreps = 100) + xlab("firmness")

# modelâs prediction
posterior1 <- as.matrix(SingleLevelModelMod)
means1 <- colMeans(posterior1)
betas <- posterior1[sample(nrow(posterior1), 100), 1:2]
blues <- color_scheme_get("brightblue")
mod1p1 <- ggplot(dat, aes(x = size, y = firmness)) +
  geom_point(color = "gray30") +
  geom_abline(intercept = betas[, 1], slope = betas[, 2], 
              color = blues[[2]], size = 0.15,  alpha = 0.5
  ) +
  geom_abline(intercept = means1[1], 
              slope = means1[2],size = 1.25,  color = blues[[6]]
) 

# Ploting
grid.arrange(plot1,mod1p1,ncol=2)

Interpretation

  • By checking the posterior predictive checks: For models that fit the data well, this type of plot will show that the draws from the posterior predictive distribution (thin light lines) and the observed data (thick dark line) have similar distributions.

  • In this case, it looks like the model does reasonably well.

  • Point estimates: A point estimate is a single value, most often a measure of central tendency (e.g., mean, median), chosen to summarize a posterior distribution. In contrast to the maximum likelihood approach, in which the point estimate (the mode) is the focus, in the Bayesian framework we are interested in the entire posterior distribution.

  • Posterior intervals (PI) and posterior standard deviation (SD): range of the model parameters in probabilistic terms

Diagnostic

  • Trace plot: shows the history of a parameter value across iterations of the chain. It is often the best thing for diagnosing common problems. Typically we look for three aspects in these trace plots:

    1. Stationarity refers to the path of each chain staying within the same high-probability portion of the posterior distribution. Notice that these traces, for example, all stick around a very stable central tendency, the center of gravity of each dimension of the posterior.
    2. Good mixing means that the chain rapidly explores the full region. It doesnât slowly wander, but rather rapidly zig-zags around.
    3. Convergence means that multiple, independent chains stick around the same region of high probability

  • Trace rank plot: distribution of the ranked samples. The lowest sample gets rank 1. The largest gets the maximum rank (the number of samples across all chains). Then we draw a histogram of these ranks for each individual chain. If the chains are exploring the same space efficiently, the histograms should be similar to one another and largely overlapping.

  • Gelman-Rubin Statistic: Intuitively, its value is 1.0 if the chains are fully converged, but its value is largerthan 1.0 if there are orphaned or stuck chains. As a heuristic, if the Gelman-Rubin statistic is greater than 1.1 or so, you should worry that perhaps the chains have not converged adequately.

  • Effective sample size Statistic: divides the actual sample size by the amount of autocorrelation. For example, 600 ESS in a chain of 10000 means that only 600 chains are independent in a total of 10000. Some authors suggest 10000 ESS as a good number.

Conclusions

  • We introduced the R package rstanarm, which is a user-friendly tool to fit single-level and more complex Bayesian regression models.

Frequentist Bayes
Researchers R.A.Fisher, Neyman, Pearson and Wald Bayes, Price and Laplace
Probability never uses or gives the probability of a hypothesis (no prior or posterior) uses probabilities for both hypotheses and data
Inference depends on the likelihood for both observed and unobserved data depends on the prior and likelihood of observed data
Conclusions p-values and confidence intervals posteriori distribution
Prior does not require a prior requires one to know or construct a âsubjective priorâ
Relevance dominated statistical practice during the 20th century dominated statistical practice before the 20th century
Computational time tends to be less computationally intensive may be computationally intensive due to integration over many parameters
Critiques p-value depends on the exact experimental setup, p-value and significance level are notoriously prone to misinterpretation subjective prior, philosophical objections to assigning probabilities to hypotheses
Defense It is objective: all statisticians will agree on the p-value, it has been used for over 100 years and we have seen tremendous scientific progress probability of hypotheses is exactly what we need to make decisions, logically rigorous, easy to communicate a result framed in terms of probabilities of hypothese.
